p data-start=3D"0" data-end=3D"113">Exactly =F0=9F=91=80, you=E2=80=99ve bu=
mped into how <strong data-start=3D"35" data-end=3D"79">Microsoft Edge (and=
 also Chrome/Firefox)</strong> handles offline webpage saving.</p>
<p data-start=3D"115" data-end=3D"138">Here=E2=80=99s the breakdown:</p>
<h3 data-start=3D"140" data-end=3D"165">=F0=9F=93=82 What you=E2=80=99re se=
eing</h3>
<ul data-start=3D"166" data-end=3D"361">
<li data-start=3D"166" data-end=3D"220">
<p data-start=3D"168" data-end=3D"220"><strong data-start=3D"168" data-end=
=3D"193"><code data-start=3D"170" data-end=3D"179">rr.html</code> (or <code=
 data-start=3D"184" data-end=3D"190">.htm</code>)</strong> =E2=86=92 the ma=
in webpage file.</p>
</li>
<li data-start=3D"221" data-end=3D"361">
<p data-start=3D"223" data-end=3D"361"><strong data-start=3D"223" data-end=
=3D"244"><code data-start=3D"225" data-end=3D"235">rr_files</code> folder</=
strong> =E2=86=92 all the supporting resources (images, CSS, JavaScript, et=
c.) that the <code data-start=3D"317" data-end=3D"324">.html</code> needs t=
o display properly offline.</p>
</li>
</ul>
<p data-start=3D"363" data-end=3D"435">This is called the **=E2=80=9CWeb Pa=
ge, complete (<em data-start=3D"405" data-end=3D"422">.htm; <em data-start=
=3D"412" data-end=3D"421">.html)=E2=80=9D</em></em> save format.</p>
<hr data-start=3D"437" data-end=3D"440">
<h3 data-start=3D"442" data-end=3D"479">=F0=9F=94=97 Why both move/delete t=
ogether?</h3>
<p data-start=3D"480" data-end=3D"548">On Windows, when a program like Edge=
 saves a webpage in that format:</p>
<ul data-start=3D"549" data-end=3D"798">
<li data-start=3D"549" data-end=3D"609">
<p data-start=3D"551" data-end=3D"609">The <code data-start=3D"555" data-en=
d=3D"562">.html</code> file and the <code data-start=3D"576" data-end=3D"58=
4">_files</code> folder are <strong data-start=3D"596" data-end=3D"606">lin=
ked</strong>.</p>
</li>
<li data-start=3D"610" data-end=3D"678">
<p data-start=3D"612" data-end=3D"678">Explorer treats them as a single log=
ical unit (=E2=80=9Ccompound file=E2=80=9D).</p>
</li>
<li data-start=3D"679" data-end=3D"798">
<p data-start=3D"681" data-end=3D"692">That=E2=80=99s why:</p>
<ul data-start=3D"695" data-end=3D"798">
<li data-start=3D"695" data-end=3D"748">
<p data-start=3D"697" data-end=3D"748">If you <strong data-start=3D"704" da=
ta-end=3D"718">delete one</strong>, Explorer deletes the pair.</p>
</li>
<li data-start=3D"751" data-end=3D"798">
<p data-start=3D"753" data-end=3D"798">If you <strong data-start=3D"760" da=
ta-end=3D"772">move one</strong>, the other comes along.</p>
</li>
</ul>
</li>
</ul>
<p data-start=3D"800" data-end=3D"901">This isn=E2=80=99t some virus or wei=
rd behavior =E2=80=94 it=E2=80=99s just Windows making sure the saved page =
doesn=E2=80=99t break.</p>
<hr data-start=3D"903" data-end=3D"906">
<h3 data-start=3D"908" data-end=3D"934">=E2=9A=99=EF=B8=8F Can you avoid th=
is?</h3>
<p data-start=3D"935" data-end=3D"995">Yes. Instead of saving as <strong da=
ta-start=3D"961" data-end=3D"985">=E2=80=9CWeb Page, complete=E2=80=9D</str=
ong>, you can:</p>
<ol data-start=3D"996" data-end=3D"1241">
<li data-start=3D"996" data-end=3D"1094">
<p data-start=3D"999" data-end=3D"1094">Save as <strong data-start=3D"1007"=
 data-end=3D"1044">=E2=80=9CWeb Page, single file (*.mhtml)=E2=80=9D</stron=
g> =E2=86=92 everything packed into <strong data-start=3D"1070" data-end=3D=
"1091">one <code data-start=3D"1076" data-end=3D"1084">.mhtml</code> file</=
strong>.</p>
</li>
<li data-start=3D"1095" data-end=3D"1192">
<p data-start=3D"1098" data-end=3D"1192">Or save as <strong data-start=3D"1=
109" data-end=3D"1134">=E2=80=9CWeb Page, HTML only=E2=80=9D</strong> =E2=
=86=92 just the <code data-start=3D"1146" data-end=3D"1153">.html</code>, b=
ut images/styles won=E2=80=99t be offline.</p>
</li>
<li data-start=3D"1193" data-end=3D"1241">
<p data-start=3D"1196" data-end=3D"1241">Or use <strong data-start=3D"1203"=
 data-end=3D"1210">PDF</strong> if you just need a snapshot.</p>
</li>
</ol>
<hr data-start=3D"1243" data-end=3D"1246">
<p data-start=3D"1248" data-end=3D"1461">=F0=9F=91=89 In short: Windows Exp=
lorer is =E2=80=9Cbinding=E2=80=9D them for convenience. They=E2=80=99re st=
ill <strong data-start=3D"1327" data-end=3D"1357">two separate files/folder=
s</strong> on disk, but Explorer performs linked operations so you don=E2=
=80=99t accidentally break the offline webpage.</p>
